<chapter xml:id="chapter-partial-orders" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Partially ordered sets</title>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<p> In many of the sets we encounter, there is some notion of elements being <q>less than or equal to</q> other elements in the set. </p>

<example><title>Comparing numbers</title><p>
	In <m>\N</m>, <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, or <m>\R</m>, we use the usual <m>\mathord{\le}</m> to describe when one number is (literally) less than or equal to another.
</p></example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-subset">
	<title>Subset relationship as a measure of relative size</title>
	<p>
	If <m>A,B</m> are subsets of a universal set <m>U</m> such that <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m>,
	we might think of <m>A</m> as being <q>less than or equal to</q> <m>B</m>.
	The relation <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>\powset{U}</m> acts very similarly to how <m>\mathord{\le}</m> acts on a set of numbers.
	</p>
</example>

<warning><p>
	The idea of <m>A \subseteq B</m> expressing a <q>less than or equal to</q>-like relationship between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is very different from cardinality-based ideas of
	<term><xref ref="definition-countable-smaller-set" text="custom">smaller</xref></term>/<term><xref ref="definition-countable-larger-set" text="custom">larger</xref></term> for sets.
	See also <xref ref="example-partial-orders-smaller-set-cardinality-not-partial-order" />.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title>Subgraph relationship as a measure of relative size</title>
	<p>
	Similar to <xref ref="example-partial-orders-subset" />,
	if <m>H</m> and <m>H'</m> are subgraphs of a graph <m>G</m> such that <m>H'</m> is a subgraph of <m>H</m>,
	we might think of <m>H'</m> as being <q>less than or equal to</q> <m>H</m>.
	That is, if we write <m>\subgraphset{G}</m> to mean the set of all subgraphs of <m>G</m>,
	then we can use the subgraph relation <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> to describe when one subgraph of <m>G</m> is <q>smaller than or equal to</q> another.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-defns-exmps">
<title>Definition and examples</title>

<p>
Notice that in each of the examples in <xref ref="section-partial-orders-motivation" />,
the notion of <q>is smaller than</q> is defined via a relation.
We will use <m>\mathord{\le}</m> on <m>\N</m> as our model for a relation on a set
that can be thought of as expressing <q>is smaller than or equal in size to.</q>
<ul>
	<li>
		Every element in the set should be <q>smaller than or equal to</q> itself,
		so the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-reflexive" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
	<li>
		Relative size should <em>never</em> be bidirectional for distinct elements in the set,
		so the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-antisymmetric" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
	<li>
		We should be able to infer size relationships from chains of them,
		so the relation should be <term><xref ref="definition-relations-transitive" text="title" /></term>.
	</li>
</ul>
Notice that these are the same properties as for an equivalence relation, <alert>except</alert> that we have flipped <term>symmetric</term> to <term>antisymmetric</term>.
Make sure to keep this straight!
<dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>partial order</title>
		<idx>partial order</idx>
		<idx><h>relation</h><h>partial order</h></idx>
		<idx><h>order</h><h>partial</h></idx>
		<p> a relation that is reflexive, <em>anti</em>symmetric, and transitive </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>partially ordered set</title>
		<idx>partially ordered set</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h></idx>
		<p> a set equipped with a particular partial order </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\mathord{\partorder}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>a \mathord{\partorder} b</m></usage>
			<description>
				<m>a</m> is related to <m>b</m> by the partial order <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m>;
				in other words, <m>a</m> is somehow <q>smaller than or same size as</q> <m>b</m>
			</description>
		</notation>
		<p> symbol for an abstract partial order </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>strictly less/smaller than</title>
		<idx><h>partial order</h><h>strict relationship</h></idx>
		<idx><h>relation</h><h>partial order</h><h>strict relationship</h></idx>
		<idx>strict partial order relationship</idx>
		<p> <m>a \partorder b</m> and <m>a \neq b</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>a \partorderstrict b</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>a \partorderstrict b</m></usage>
			<description><m>a \partorder b</m> but <m>a \neq b</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>a</m> is strictly less/smaller than <m>b</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<warning><p>
	We previously used the symbol <m>\mathord{\subgraph}</m> to mean exclusively
	<q><term><xref ref="notationdef-graphs-subgraph" text="custom">is a subgraph of</xref></term>,</q>
	but that was in anticipation of the introduction of this symbol to now mean a general partial order.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title><q>Less than or equal to</q> versus <q>less than</q> on sets of numbers</title>
	<p> The usual notion of <m>\mathord{\leq}</m> is a partial order on <m>\N</m> (or <m>\Z</m> or <m>\Q</m> or <m>\R</m>), but <m>\mathord{\lt}</m> is not. </p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Subset relation</title>
	<p> For every set <m>U</m>, the relation <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> is a partial order on <m>\powset{U}</m>, but <m>\mathord{\subsetneqq}</m> is not. </p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Subgraph relation</title>
	<p> For every graph <m>G</m>, the subgraph relation <m>\mathord{\subgraph}</m> is a partial order on <m>\subgraphset{G}</m>, the set of subgraphs of <m>G</m>. </p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-smaller-set-cardinality-not-partial-order">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::smaller.set.cardinality.not.partial.order} -->
	<title>Comparing cardinalities</title>
	<p>
	Suppose <m>U</m> is a universal set, and consider the collection of <em>finite</em> subsets of <m>U</m>.
	Then we have a natural way to compare sizes of these subsets: write <m>A \mathrel{R} B</m> to mean <m>\card{A} \le \card{B}</m>.
	However, this relation is not a partial order as it is not antisymmetric.
	This is because it is possible to have both <m>A \mathrel{R} B</m> and <m>B \mathrel{R} A</m> with <m>A \neq B</m>, in the case that <m>\card{A} = \card{B}</m>.
	Changing the relation to mean <m>\card{A} \lneqq \card{B}</m> doesn't help,
	since then it wouldn't be reflexive.
	</p><p>
	Now suppose the universal set <m>U</m> is infinite and consider <em>all</em>
	(hence possibly infinite) subsets of <m>U</m>.
	In this case we have a more general idea of
	<term><xref ref="definition-countable-smaller-set" text="custom">smaller</xref></term> and <term><xref ref="definition-countable-larger-set" text="custom">larger</xref></term>,
	where <m>A</m> is smaller than <m>B</m> if there exists an injection <m>A \ifuncto B</m> but no bijection <m>A \to B</m>.
	This more general notion of size comparison via cardinality suffers the same flaws as in the finite set case,
	as it is not reflexive, and if we try to fix that by adding <q>or same size as</q> then it will not be antisymmetric.
	</p><p>
	However, in both finite and (possibly) infinite cases, we <em>can</em> turn cardinality comparison into a partial order using <q>smaller than or <em>equal</em> to</q>, where <q>smaller</q> must mean strictly smaller in terms of cardinality, but <q>equal</q> means <em>equality of sets</em> rather than equality of cardinality.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>English alphabetic order</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>\Sigma = \EngAlphabet</m>,
	and consider
	<term>alphabetic order</term>
	<idx>alphabetic order</idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>alphabetic</h></idx>
	on the set of words <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>;
	<eg />
	<md><mrow>
		\mathrm{gqtiu} \amp \partorder \mathrm{ppb}, \amp
		\mathrm{aaay} \amp \partorder \mathrm{aaaz}, \amp
		\mathrm{aaa} \amp \partorder \mathrm{aaaa}.
	</mrow></md>
	Alphabetic ordering is a partial order on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-lexicographic-on-words">
	<title>Lexicographic order</title>
	<idx>lexicographic order</idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>lexicographic</h></idx>
	<idx>dictionary order</idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>dictionary</h></idx>
	<p>
	We can generalize the previous example:
	if <m>\Sigma</m> is a partially ordered alphabet set equipped with partial order <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m>,
	then we may inductively define a partial order <m>\mathord{\words{\partorder}}</m> on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> by:
	<ul>
		<li>
			<m>\emptyword \words{\partorder} w</m> for every <m>w \in \words{\Sigma}</m>,
			where <m>\emptyword</m> is the empty word;
		</li>
		<li>
			for <m>a,b \in \Sigma</m>,
			considering these letters as words of length <m>1</m> in <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>
			take <m>a \words{\partorder} b</m> to mean <m>a \partorder b</m> in <m>\Sigma</m>;
		</li>
		<li><p>
			for letters <m>a_1, a_2 \in \Sigma</m> and words <m>w_1, w_2 \in \words{\Sigma}</m>,
			take <m>a_1 w_1 \words{\partorder} a_2 w_2</m> to mean that either
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li> <m>a_1 \ne a_2</m> and <m>a_1 \partorder a_2</m>, or </li>
				<li> <m>a_1 = a_2</m> and <m>w_1 \words{\partorder} w_2</m>. </li>
			</ol>
		</p></li>
	</ul>
	This is called <term>lexicographic</term> or <term>dictionary order</term> on <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Ordering Cartesian products</title>
	<idx>lexicographic order</idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>lexicographic</h></idx>
	<p>
	We can employ a similar tactic for Cartesian products.
	If <m>\mathord{\partorder_A}, \mathord{\partorder_B}</m> are partial orders on sets <m>A,B</m>, respectively,
	we can define a partial order <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> on <m>A \cartprod B</m> by
	allowing <m>(a_1, b_1) \partorder (a_2, b_2)</m> to mean that either
	<ol marker="(i)">
		<li> <m>a_1 \ne a_2</m> and <m>a_1 \partorder_A a_2</m>, or </li>
		<li> <m>a_1 = a_2</m> and <m>b_1 \partorder_B b_2</m>. </li>
	</ol>
	This is also called <term>lexicographic order</term>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-lt-gt-inverse">
	<title>Larger/greater than is a partial order</title>
	<idx>dual order</idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>dual</h></idx>
	<p>
	We can flip <q>smaller/less than or equal to</q> around to <q>larger/greater than or equal to.</q>
	For example, for elements <m>m,n \in \N</m>, write <m>m \partorder n</m> to mean <m>m \ge n</m>.
	Then <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> is a partial order on <m>\N</m>.
	</p><p>
	This is an instance of a more general pattern.
	Given a partial order <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> on a set <m>A</m>,
	the <xref ref="definition-relations-inverse" text="custom">inverse relation</xref>
	<m>\mathord{\inv{\partorder}}</m>,
	where <m>a_1 \mathrel{\inv{\partorder}} a_2</m> means <m>a_2 \partorder a_1</m>,
	is also a partial order on <m>A</m>,
	called the <term>dual order</term>.
	<idx><h>partial order</h><h>dual</h></idx>
	<idx><h>relation</h><h>partial order</h><h>dual</h></idx>
	<idx><h>order</h><h>dual</h></idx>
	</p>
	<!-- TODO XREF to activity or exercise? -->
</example>

<!-- TODO should all this "pulling back" stuff be transferred to activities ? -->
<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-encoded-powset-pull-back">
	<title>Transferring <m>\le</m> on <m>\N</m> to a power set</title>
	<p> Let <m>A = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>, and let us <q>encode</q> each element of <m>\powset{A}</m> by the following algorithm. </p>
	<p> Given input element <m>X \in \powset{A}</m> (that is, given input <m>X</m> that is a subset of <m>A</m>):
	<ol marker="(i)">
		<li> Initialize encoded value <m>r = 0</m>. </li>
		<li> If <m>X</m> contains <m>a</m>, add <m>1</m> to <m>r</m>. </li>
		<li> If <m>X</m> contains <m>b</m>, add <m>2</m> to <m>r</m>. </li>
		<li> If <m>X</m> contains <m>c</m>, add <m>4</m> to <m>r</m>. </li>
		<li> If <m>X</m> contains <m>d</m>, add <m>8</m> to <m>r</m>. </li>
		<li> Set <m>\operatorname{encode}(X)</m> to be the final value of <m>r</m>. </li>
	</ol>
	For example,
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\operatorname{encode}\bbrac{\{b\}} \amp = 2, \amp
			\operatorname{encode}(\emptyset) \amp = 0,
		</mrow><mrow>
			\operatorname{encode}\bbrac{\{a,c\}} \amp = 1 + 4 = 5, \amp
			\operatorname{encode}(A) \amp = 1 + 2 + 4 + 8 = 15.
		</mrow>
	</md>
	This encoding process is one-to-one; that is, no two subsets of <m>A</m> will output the same encoded value.
	</p><p>
	Now define <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> on <m>\powset{A}</m> by taking <m>X \partorder Y</m> to mean <m>\operatorname{encode}(X) \le \operatorname{encode}(Y)</m>.
	For example,
	<md><mrow> \{a,b,c\} \amp \partorder \{d\}, \amp \{a,d\} \amp \partorder \{b,d\}, </mrow></md>
	and both
	<md><mrow> \emptyset \amp \partorder X, \amp X \amp \partorder A </mrow></md>
	are true for every subset <m>X \subseteq A</m>.
	</p><p>
	The facts that <m>\mathord{\le}</m> is a partial order on <m>\N</m> and that this encoding process is one-to-one will combine to make <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> a partial order.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-order-pull-back">
	<title>Pulling a partial order back through an injection</title>
	<p>
	Generalizing <xref ref="example-partial-orders-encoded-powset-pull-back" />,
	suppose <m>\ifuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is an injection where <m>B</m> is partially ordered by <m>\mathord{\partorder_B}</m>.
	Then we can <q>pull back</q> the partial order on <m>B</m> to create a partial order on <m>A</m> as follows:
	define <m>a_1 \preceq_A a_2</m> to mean that <m>f(a_1) \preceq_B f(a_2)</m> is true.
	Note that the assumption that <m>f</m> is injective is essential to guarantee that <m>\mathord{\partorder_A}</m> will be antisymmetric.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-graph">
<title>Graph for a partial order</title>

<p><dl><li>
	<title>Hasse diagram</title>
	<idx>Hasse diagram</idx>
	<p>
	a diagram for the graph for a partial order on a <em>finite</em> set <m>A</m>,
	omitting reflexive loops and transitive <q>composite</q> edges,
	and placing <q>smaller</q> elements <em>lower</em> on the diagram instead of using arrows
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-divides-hasse-diagram">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::divides.hasse.diagram} -->
	<title>Hasse diagram for division of integers</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>A = \{2,4,6,8,10,12\}</m>.
	The Hasse diagram of the partial order <m>\mathord{\mid}</m> (<ie /> <q>divides</q>) on <m>A</m> appears in <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-hasse-divides" />.
	Notice that <m>2</m> is not joined directly to either <m>8</m> or <m>12</m>, since we can use transitivity and the facts that <m>2 \mid 4</m> and <m>2 \mid 6</m> to infer <m>2 \mid 8</m> and <m>2 \mid 12</m>, respectively, from the diagram.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-partial-orders-hasse-divides">
		<caption>The Hasse diagram for the <q>divides</q> partial order on a finite set of integers.</caption>
		<image width="30%">
			<description>Hasse diagram for the <q>divides</q> partial order.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/hasse-divides.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

<remark><p> See <xref ref="example-graphs-divides" /> for another example of a graph for the <q>divides</q> relation. </p></remark>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-pow-set-graph">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::pow.set.graph.copy} -->
	<title>Hasse diagram for subset order</title>
	<p>
	The graph from <xref ref="example-graphs-pow-set" /> has been reproduced in <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-hasse-subset" /> as a Hasse diagram,
	and represents the partial order <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>\powset{\{a,b,c\}}</m>.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-partial-orders-hasse-subset">
		<caption>The Hasse diagram for the subset partial order on the power set of a finite set.</caption>
		<image width="55%">
			<description>Hasse diagram for the subset partial order.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/hasse-subset.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-total">
<title>Total orders</title>

<p><dl>
	<li>
		<title>comparable elements</title>
		<idx>comparable</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>comparable elements</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>comparable elements</h></idx>
		<p>
		elements <m>a,b</m> in a partially ordered set such that either <m>a \partorder b</m> or <m>b \partorder a</m>
		</p>
	</li>\mathord{
	<li>
		<title>incomparable elements</title>
		<idx>incomparable</idx>
		<idx>incomparable</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>incomparable elements</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>incomparable elements</h></idx>
		<p> elements that are not comparable </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Comparable and incomparable subsets</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>U</m> represent some universal set containing at least two elements,
	and consider <m>\powset{U}</m> partially ordered by <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>.
	<ul>
		<li> Both the empty set <m>\emptyset</m> and the universal set <m>U</m> are comparable to every element of <m>\powset{U}</m>. </li>
		<li> For <m>x,y\in U</m> with <m>x\ne y</m>, then <m>\{x\},\{y\}</m> are incomparable. </li>
		<li>
			In fact, for every non-empty, proper subset <m>A \subsetneqq U</m> there exists a subset <m>B \subseteq U</m> which is incomparable to <m>A</m>: take <m>B = \cmplmnt{A}</m>.
		</li>
	</ul>
	However, do not let the second two points above lead you astray: it is not necessary for subsets to be disjoint in order to be incomparable.
	As long as each of a pair of subsets contains an element that the other doesn't, then the two will be incomparable by <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p><dl>
	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-total">
	<!-- \label{DEFN::total.order} -->
		<title>total order</title>
		<idx>total order</idx>
		<idx><h>partial order</h><h>total</h></idx>
		<idx><h>relation</h><h>partial order</h><h>total</h></idx>
		<idx><h>order</h><h>total</h></idx>
		<p> a partial order on a set such that <em>every</em> pair of elements is comparable </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>totally ordered set</title>
		<idx>totally ordered set</idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>totally ordered</h></idx>
		<p> a set equipped with a total order </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Subset order is not total</title>
	<p> For universal set <m>U</m>, order <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>\powset{U}</m> is not total except when <m>\card{U} \le 1</m>. </p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Usual order of numbers is total</title>
	<p> Our usual order for numbers, <m>\mathord{\leq}</m>, is a total order on <m>\N</m>, on <m>\Z</m>, on <m>\Q</m>, or on <m>\R</m>. </p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Total order on alphabet induces total order on words</title>
	<p>
	If <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> is a total order on an alphabet <m>\Sigma</m>,
	then the lexicographic order <m>\words{\partorder}</m> described in <xref ref="example-partial-orders-lexicographic-on-words" /> is a total order on the set of words <m>\words{\Sigma}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-order-total-pull-back">
	<title>Pulling back a total order through an injection</title>
	<p>
	If <m>B</m> is totally ordered and we use an injection <m>\ifuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m> to <q>pull back</q> the order on <m>B</m> to an order on <m>A</m>
	(see <xref ref="example-partial-order-pull-back" />), then the newly created order on <m>A</m> will also be total.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-countable-can-be-totally-ordered">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::countable.set.can.be.totally.ordered} -->
	<title>Countable can be totally ordered</title>
	<p>
	If <m>A</m> is a <term><xref ref="definition-countable-countably-infinite" text="title" /></term> set,
	then there exists a bijection <m>\funcdef{f}{\N}{A}</m>.
	We can use the inverse <m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{A}{\N}</m> to <q>pull back</q> the usual total order <m>\mathord{\le}</m> on <m>\N</m> to a total order on <m>A</m>
	(see <xref ref="example-partial-order-total-pull-back" />).
	</p><p>
	Another point of view on this is that our bijection <m>f</m> creates an infinite sequence
	<me> a_0, a_1, a_2, \dotsc </me>,
	where each element of <m>A</m> appears exactly once.
	This sequence can be turned into a specification of the total order on <m>A</m> by just turning the commas into <m>\mathord{\le}</m> symbols:
	<me> a_0 \le a_1 \le a_2 \le \dotsb </me>.
	</p>
</example>

<remark xml:id="remark-partial-orders-finite-can-be-totally-ordered"><p>
	The pattern of <xref ref="example-partial-orders-countable-can-be-totally-ordered" /> becomes even simpler when we apply it to a <em>finite</em> set:
	a total order on a finite set is no different than an ordering of the set elements into a list,
	as
	<me> a_0, a_1, a_2, \dotsc, a_n </me>
	can simply be turned into
	<me> a_0 \le a_1 \le a_2 \le \dotsb \le a_n </me>,
	and vice versa.
</p></remark>

<question><statement><p>
	If <m>A</m> is a finite, totally ordered set, what does the corresponding Hasse diagram look like?
</p></statement></question>

<p> The answer to this question is contained in <xref ref="remark-partial-orders-finite-can-be-totally-ordered" />. </p>

<fact><p> A partial order on a finite set is total if and only if its Hasse diagram forms a single vertical line. </p></fact>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-totally-ordered-hasse-diagram">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::totally.ordered.hasse.diagram} -->
	<title>A totally ordered finite set</title>
	<p>
	<xref ref="figure-partial-orders-total-order-powers-of-two" /> exhibits the Hasse diagram for the total order <m>\mathord{\mid}</m> on the set <m>\{2,4,8,16,32\}</m>,
	though we have drawn the diagram on a slant from the vertical to be make it easier to see the entire diagram at a glance.
	</p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-partial-orders-total-order-powers-of-two">
		<caption>A Hasse diagram of a totally ordered set.</caption>
		<image width="40%">
			<description>A Hasse diagram of a totally ordered set.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/hasse-total.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-max-min">
<title>Maximal/minimal elements</title>

<p>
Each of the following definitions are for a subset <m>B</m> of a partially ordered set <m>A</m>.
<dl>

	<li>
		<title>upper bound</title>
		<idx>upper bound</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>upper bound</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>upper bound</h></idx>
		<p> an element <m>u \in A</m> such that <m>b \partorder u</m> for all <m>b \in B</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-least-upper-bound">
		<title>least upper bound</title>
		<idx>least upper bound</idx>
		<idx><h>upper bound</h><h>least</h></idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>upper bound</h><h>least</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>least upper bound</h></idx>
		<p> an upper bound for <m>B \subseteq A</m> that is less than every other upper bound </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>maximum element</title>
		<idx>maximum element</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>maximum element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>maximum element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>element</h><h>maximum</h></idx>
		<p> an upper bound for <m>B</m> that is contained in <m>B</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>lower bound</title>
		<idx>lower bound</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>lower bound</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>lower bound</h></idx>
		<p> an element <m>\ell \in A</m> such that <m>\ell \partorder b</m> for all <m>b \in B</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-greatest-lower-bound">
		<title>greatest lower bound</title>
		<idx>greatest lower bound</idx>
		<idx><h>lower bound</h><h>greatest</h></idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>lower bound</h><h>greatest</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>greatest lower bound</h></idx>
		<p> a lower bound for <m>B \subseteq A</m> that is greater than every other lower bound </p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>minimum element</title>
		<idx>minimum element</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>minimum element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>minimum element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>element</h><h>minimum</h></idx>
		<p> a lower bound for <m>B</m> that is contained in <m>B</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<warning><p><ol>
	<li> An upper or lower bound does <em>not</em> need to belong to the subset for which it is a bound. </li>
	<li> A set (or subset) does not necessarily have either a maximum or minimum element. </li>
</ol></p></warning>

<fact>
	<statement><p>
		If a subset of a partially ordered set contains a maximum element, then that maximum element is unique.
		And similarly for a minimum element.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><p> You are asked to prove this in <xref ref="activity-partial-orders-prove-maximum-unique" />. </p></proof>
</fact>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-max-min-bound-in-R">
	<title>Maximums, minimums, and bounds in <m>\R</m></title>
	<p>
	Consider the usual (total) order <m>\mathord{\leq}</m> on <m>\R</m>.
	<ul>
		<li> The full set <m>\R</m> has neither a maximum nor minimum element. </li>
		<li>
			The subset <m>(0,1)</m> has many upper bounds (anything <m>\geq 1</m>) and many lower bounds (anything <m>\leq 0</m>).
			However, we would refer to <m>1</m> as the
			<term><xref ref="definition-partial-orders-least-upper-bound" text="title" /></term>
			and to <m>0</m> as the
			<term><xref ref="definition-partial-orders-greatest-lower-bound" text="title" /></term>
			of <m>(0,1)</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			The subset <m>(0,1)</m> has no maximum or minimum element.
			However, the subset <m>[0,1]</m> has maximum <m>1</m> and minimum <m>0</m>.
		</li>
	</ul>
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Maximums, minimums, and bounds in a power set</title>
	<p>
	Suppose <m>U</m> is a universal set, and consider <m>\powset{U}</m> partially ordered by <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> as usual.
	In the full set <m>\powset{U}</m>, the unique maximum element is <m>U</m>, which is just another way of saying that every element of <m>\powset{U}</m> is a subset of <m>U</m>.
	And the unique minimum element is <m>\emptyset</m>, which is just another way of saying that the empty set is a subset of every subset of <m>U</m>.
	</p><p>
	Now consider a subset <m>\mathscr{A} \subseteq \powset{U}</m>, so that <m>\mathscr{A}</m> is a collection of subsets of <m>U</m>.
	Because of the existence of maximum and minimum elements, these elements also serve as an upper and lower bound, respectively, for <m>\mathscr{A}</m>.
	However, one can also find a <em>least</em> upper bound for <m>\mathscr{A}</m> by taking the union of all the subsets of <m>U</m> contained in <m>\mathscr{A}</m>,
	and one can find a greatest lower bound by taking the intersection of all the subsets of <m>U</m> contained in <m>\mathscr{A}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
The next two definitions are stated for elements in a partially ordered set,
but could also be understood for elements in a subset of a partially ordered set, as every subset of a partially ordered set is also a partially ordered set.
<dl>
	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-maximal">
	<!-- \label{DEFN::maximal} -->
		<title>maximal element</title>
		<idx>maximal element</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>maximal element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>maximal element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>element</h><h>maximal</h></idx>
		<p> an element for which no other element is larger </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-minimal">
		<title>minimal element</title>
		<idx>minimal element</idx>
		<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>minimal element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>minimal element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>element</h><h>minimal</h></idx>
		<p> an element for which no other element is smaller </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<remark><p>
	The difference between <term>maximum</term> and <term>maximal</term> is subtle.
	A maximum element must be larger than (and hence comparable to) <em>every</em> other element of <m>A</m>,
	while a maximal element must only be larger than every other element of <m>A</m> <em>to which it is comparable</em>.
	The distinction between <em>minimum</em> and <em>minimal</em> is similar.
</p></remark>

<claim xml:id="test-partial-orders-maximal-minimal">
	<title>Maximal/minimal elements</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>maximal/minimal elements</h></idx>
	<idx><h>minimal element</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>maximal element</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>minimal element</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>maximal element</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>minimal element, Test for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>maximal element, Test for</h></idx>
	<idx><h>element</h><h>minimal</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<idx><h>element</h><h>maximal</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<p><ol>
		<li xml:id="test-partial-orders-maximal-minimal-maximal">
		<!-- \label{TEST::maximal.element} -->
			To verify that <m>\overline{m} \in A</m> is maximal, prove either the original definition
			<me> (\forall x \in A)({x \neq \overline{m}} \lgcimplies {\overline{m} \npartorder x}) </me>,
			or prove the equivalent contrapositive formulation
			<me> (\forall x \in A)({\overline{m} \partorder x} \lgcimplies {x = \overline{m}}) </me>.
		</li>
		<li>
			To verify that <m>\underline{m} \in A</m> is minimal, prove either the original definition
			<me> (\forall x \in A)({x \neq \underline{m}} \lgcimplies {x \npartorder \underline{m}}) </me>,
			or prove the equivalent contrapositive formulation
			<me> (\forall x \in A)({x \partorder \underline{m}} \lgcimplies {x = \underline{m}}) </me>.
		</li>
	</ol></p>
</claim>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-connected-components-are-maximal">
<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::connected.components.are.maximal} -->
	<title>Connected components are maximal</title>
	<p> Consider the graph <m>G</m> in <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-example-connected-components-are-maximal" />. </p>
	<figure xml:id="figure-partial-orders-example-connected-components-are-maximal">
		<caption>An example non-connected graph.</caption>
		<image width="30%">
			<description>An example non-connected graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/components-are-maximal.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	Let <m>\subgraphset{G}</m> represent the collection of subgraphs of <m>G</m>,
	partially ordered by the subgraph relation.
	(By my count, <m>\card{\subgraphset{G}} = 110</m>.)
	Let <m>\connectedsubgraphset{G}</m> represent the collection of <em>connected</em> subgraphs of <m>G</m>.
	(By my count, <m>\card{\connectedsubgraphset{G}} = 15</m>.)
	A maximal elements of <m>\connectedsubgraphset{G}</m> would have to be a connected subgraph of <m>G</m> that is contained in no larger connected subgraph of <m>G</m> <mdash />
	but this is precisely the definition of <term>connected component</term>.
	Hence <m>\connectedsubgraphset{G}</m> has three maximal elements, the three connected components you see in <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-example-connected-components-are-maximal" />.
	However, a maximum element of <m>\connectedsubgraphset{G}</m> would be a connected subgraph of <m>G</m> which contains every other connected subgraph of <m>G</m>,
	and the existence of multiple connected components in this example non-connected graph makes such a subgraph impossible.
	</p>
</example>

<remark><p>
	If you compare both our
	<xref ref="definition-paths-connected-component-working" text="custom">informal definition</xref> and
	<xref ref="definition-paths-connected-component-formal" text="custom">formal definition</xref>
	of <term>connected component</term>
	with our definition of <term><xref ref="definition-partial-orders-maximal" text="title" /></term>
	and our <xref ref="test-partial-orders-maximal-minimal" text="custom">Test for Maximal/Minimal Elements</xref>,
	you should find that the definition of <term>connected component</term> means precisely a <term>maximal</term> subgraph with respect to the property of being connected.
</p></remark>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement>
		<p>
		Let <m>A = \{a,b,c\}</m>.
		Given the Hasse diagram for <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>P = \powset{A}\smallsetminus\{A\}</m>
		in <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-snipped-subseteq-powset" />,
		determine all maximal/maximum/minimal/minimum elements, if they exist.
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-partial-orders-snipped-subseteq-powset">
			<caption>The Hasse diagram for <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on an <q>uncapped</q> power set.</caption>
			<image width="45%">
				<description>The Hasse diagram for <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on an <q>uncapped</q> power set.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/hasse-uncapped-powset.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		The element <m>\{a,b\}</m> is maximal, since each node in the Hasse diagram that is adjacent to <m>\{a,b\}</m> is below it.
		The same reasoning confirms that <m>\{a,c\}</m>, and <m>\{b,c\}</m> of are also maximal.
		However, none of them is a maximum, since none of them is larger than the other two.
		</p><p>
		The element <m>\emptyset</m> of <m>P</m> is a minimal element,
		since each node that is adjacent to it is above it.
		And it is the only minimal element.
		Furthermore, <m>\emptyset</m> is the minimum element, since for every other node there is a walk upwards from <m>\emptyset</m> to that node.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<warning><p>
	Just drawing a node higher or lower in a Hasse diagram does not necessarily make it larger or smaller, respectively, when compared to other elements via the partial order.
	For example, in the Hasse diagram of <xref ref="figure-partial-orders-snipped-subseteq-powset" />,
	we could have drawn the node for <m>\{a,c\}</m> at a higher location,
	but that would not make it larger than <m>\{a,b\}</m> and <m>\{b,c\}</m>,
	since there still would not have been any edges or chains of edges from <m>\{a,c\}</m> downward to those other two nodes.
</p></warning>

<fact xml:id="fact-partial-orders-maxmin-imum-is-the-only-maxmin-imal">
<!-- \label{FACT::max.min.imum.is.only.max.min.imal} -->
	<statement><p>
		If the partially ordered set <m>A</m> has a maximum element, then that element is also the only maximal element of <m>A</m>.
		Similarly, the minimum element, if it exists, is the only minimal element of <m>A</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		Assume <m>A</m> has a maximum element.
		Then every element of <m>A</m> is both comparable to and smaller than that maximum element,
		so no element is larger than it.
		Therefore, this maximum must be maximal.
		And no other element could be maximal, because to be maximal means there are no elements which are larger.
		But our maximum element is always larger.
	</p></proof>
</fact>

<warning><p>
	A maximum element must be maximal and must be the <em>only</em> maximal.
	But a maximal element, even if it is the only one, need not be the maximum.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title>A partially ordered set with exactly one maximal element but no maximum element</title>
	<p>
	Consider
	<me> A = \{3\} \union \{2,4,8,16,32,64,\dotsc,2^n,\dotsc\}, </me>
	partially ordered by <m>\mathord{\mid}</m>, the <q>divides</q> relation.
	There is no element of <m>A</m> that is divisible by <m>3</m> (except <m>3</m> itself),
	so there is no element of <m>A</m> that is larger than <m>3</m>.
	Therefore, <m>3</m> is maximal.
	Moreover, <m>3</m> is the only maximal element in <m>A</m>, since every power of <m>2</m> divides the next power of <m>2</m>.
	However, there is no maximum element in <m>A</m>, since there is no element of <m>A</m> which is divisible by every other element of <m>A</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>A partially ordered set with infinitely many maximal/minimal elements but no maximum/minimum element</title>
	<p>
	Consider <m>\mathscr{A} \subsetneqq \powset{\N}</m>, where <me> \mathscr{A} = \powset{\N} \relcmplmnt \{\emptyset,\N\} </me>.
	So <m>\mathscr{A}</m> is the set of all nonempty, proper subsets of <m>\N</m>.
	Under the partial order <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>, <m>\mathscr{A}</m> has neither a maximum nor a minimum element,
	but for every <m>n \in \N</m>, <m>\{n\}</m> is a minimal element and <m>\N \relcmplmnt \{n\}</m> is a maximal element of <m>\mathscr{A}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-partial-orders-top-sorting">
<title>Topological sorting</title>

<p>
Sometimes we want to turn a partial order into a total order.
What makes an order <term>partial</term> instead of <term>total</term> is the presence of pairs of incomparable elements.
So to convert our partial order into a total order we just need to impose an order relation on those previously incomparable element pairs.
However, for each pair of incomparable elements there is a choice to be made of which will become the smaller and which the larger in the new total order.
And we cannot carry out these choices completely arbitrarily,
because we risk contradicting the required properties of a partial order
(see <xref ref="example-partial-orders-failed-top-sorting" />).
</p>

<p>
The following definitions apply to a partial order <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m> on a set <m>A</m>.
<dl>
	<li xml:id="definition-partial-orders-compatible-total-order">
		<title>compatible total order</title>
		<idx><h>total order</h><h>compatible</h></idx>
		<idx><h>partial order</h><h>total</h><h>compatible</h></idx>
		<idx><h>order</h><h>total</h><h>compatible</h></idx>
		<p>
		a total order <m>\mathord{\le}</m> on <m>A</m> such that if <m>a_1 \partorder a_2</m> then <m>a_1 \le a_2</m>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>topological sorting</title>
		<idx>topological sorting</idx>
		<p> a process for determining a compatible total order </p>
	</li>
</dl>
</p>

<example xml:id="example-partial-orders-failed-top-sorting">
	<title>A failed attempt at topological sorting</title>
	<p>
	The relation <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> on <m>\powset{\N}</m> is a partial order but not a total order.
	Consider what happens when we begin trying to build a total order on <m>\powset{\N}</m> out of <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m> by choosing relations between previously incomparable elements arbitrarily.
	<ul>
		<li>
			Elements <m>\{1\},\{2,3\}</m> are <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>-incomparable;
			choose <m>\{2,3\} \le \{1\}</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			Elements <m>\{1\},\{2\}</m> are <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>-incomparable; choose <m>\{1\} \le \{2\}</m>.
		</li>
		<li> <ellipsis /> </li>
	</ul>
	Now, <m>\{2\} \subseteq \{2,3\}</m> is already true, so to be compatible we must set <m>\{2\} \leq \{2,3\}</m> in the new total order.
	But now <m>\{1\} \leq \{2\} \leq \{2,3\}</m> would dictate <m>\{1\} \leq \{2,3\}</m> to satisfy the transitive property,
	but this contradicts our first arbitrary choice above.
	</p>
</example>

<note><p>
	If <m>A</m> is countable, whether finite or countably infinite,
	then specifying a total order on <m>A</m> amounts to writing the elements of <m>A</m> in an ordered list.
	(See <xref ref="example-partial-orders-countable-can-be-totally-ordered" />
	and <xref ref="remark-partial-orders-finite-can-be-totally-ordered" />.)
	In that case, topological sorting amounts to creating such an ordered list so that if <m>a \partorder b</m> then <m>a</m> appears before <m>b</m> in the list.
</p></note>

<algorithm xml:id="algorithm-partial-orders-top-sorting">
<!-- \label{ALGO::topological.sorting} -->
	<title>Topological sorting</title>
	<idx><h>partially ordered set</h><h>topological sorting</h></idx>
	<idx><h>set(s)</h><h>partially ordered</h><h>topological sorting</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Algorithm</h><h>topological sorting</h></idx>
	<p>
	If <m>A</m> is a <em>finite</em> partially ordered set with respect to <m>\mathord{\partorder}</m>,
	we can specify a compatible total order <m>\mathord{\leq}</m> on <m>A</m> by writing the elements of <m>A</m> in a list
	<me> a_0 \leq a_1 \leq \dotsb \leq a_{n-1} </me> as follows, where <m>n = \card{A}</m>.
	<ol>
		<li> Initialize <m>i = 0</m> and <m>A_0 = A</m>. </li>
		<li xml:id="algorithm-partial-orders-top-sorting-choice-step">
		<!-- \label{ALGO::topological.sorting::choice.step} -->
			Choose a minimal element of <m>A_i</m>;
			let <m>a_i</m> represent the chosen element.
		</li>
		<li>
			Set <m>A_{i+1} = A_i \relcmplmnt \{a_i\}</m>
			(<ie /> create a smaller partially ordered set by discarding <m>a_i</m>).
		</li>
		<li>
			Increment <m>i</m> by <m>1</m>.
			If <m>i \lt n</m> then go back to <xref ref="algorithm-partial-orders-top-sorting-choice-step" text="type-local">Step</xref>.
			Otherwise, if <m>i = n</m> then <m>A_i</m> should now be empty, so stop <mdash /> the desired compatible order has now been specified.
		</li>
	</ol>
	</p>
</algorithm>

<note><p>
	In <xref ref="algorithm-partial-orders-top-sorting-choice-step" text="type-local">Step</xref> of the algorithm,
	if <m>A_i</m> contains a <em>minimum</em> element, then you must choose that element, since in that case no other minimal element can exist
	(see the <xref ref="fact-partial-orders-maxmin-imum-is-the-only-maxmin-imal" />).
</p></note>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p>
		Consider
		<me>
			A = \powset{\{0,1,2\}}
			= \bigl\{ \emptyset, \{0\}, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{0,1\}, \{0,2\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}
		</me>.
		Apply <xref ref="algorithm-partial-orders-top-sorting" /> to determine a total order <m>\mathord{\leq}</m> on <m>A</m> that is compatible with <m>\mathord{\subseteq}</m>.
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<title>Algorithm solution</title>
		<p>
		In <m>A_0 = A</m>, we must choose <m>a_0 = \emptyset</m>, since it is the minimum.
		Now remove <m>a_0</m> so that
		<me> A_1 = \bigl\{ \{0\}, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{0,1\}, \{0,2\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}. </me>
		Choose a minimal element from <m>A_1</m>: let <m>a_1 = \{2\}</m>.
		Now remove <m>a_1</m>; set
		<me> A_2 = \bigl\{ \{0\}, \{1\}, \{0,1\}, \{0,2\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}. </me>
		Choose a minimal element from <m>A_2</m>: let <m>a_2 = \{0\}</m>.
		Now remove <m>a_2</m>; set
		<me> A_3 = \bigl\{ \{1\}, \{0,1\}, \{0,2\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}. </me>
		Choose a minimal element from <m>A_3</m>: let <m>a_3 = \{0,2\}</m>.
		Now remove <m>a_3</m>; set
		<me> A_4 = \bigl\{ \{1\}, \{0,1\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}. </me>
		We must choose <m>a_4 = \{1\}</m>, since it is the minimum in <m>A_4</m>.
		Now remove <m>a_4</m>; set
		<me> A_5 = \bigl\{ \{0,1\}, \{1,2\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}. </me>
		Choose a minimal element from <m>A_5</m>:
		let <m>a_5 = \{1,2\}</m>.
		Now remove <m>a_5</m>; set
		<m> A_6 = \bigl\{ \{0,1\}, \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}</m>.
		We must choose <m>a_6 = \{0,1\}</m>, since it is the minimum in <m>A_6</m>.
		There is only one element left; set <m>A_7 = \bigl\{ \{0,1,2\} \bigr\}</m> and choose <m>a_7 = \{0,1,2\}</m>.
		So we have
		<me>
			\emptyset \leq \{2\} \leq \{0\} \leq \{0,2\}
			\leq \{1\} \leq \{1,2\} \leq \{0,1\} \leq \{0,1,2\}.
		</me>
		Notice that the maximum element of <m>A</m> ended up at the <q>top</q> of the total order and the minimum element was forced to the <q>bottom.</q>
	</p></solution>
	<solution>
		<title>Graphical solution</title>
		<p>
		We can perform the algorithm of topological sorting graphically;
		at each step, choose a vertex that has no adjacent vertices below it in the graph,
		then cross that vertex and any adjacent edges out of the graph.
		</p>
		<figure>
			<caption>Example of a graphical approach to topological sorting.</caption>
			<sbsgroup>
				<sidebyside>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_0 = \emptyset</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>First step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/0.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_1 = \{2\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Second step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
				</sidebyside>
				<sidebyside>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_2 = \{0\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Third step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_3 = \{0,2\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Fourth step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/3.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
				</sidebyside>
				<sidebyside>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_4 = \{1\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Fifth step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/4.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_5 = \{1,2\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Sixth step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/5.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
				</sidebyside>
				<sidebyside>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_6 = \{0,1\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Seventh step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/6.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
					<figure>
						<caption>Choose <m>a_7 = \{0,1,2\}</m>.</caption>
						<image>
							<description>Eighth step in a graphical approach to topological sorting.</description>
							<latex-image><xi:include href="partial-orders.d/top-sort.d/7.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
						</image>
					</figure>
				</sidebyside>
			</sbsgroup>
		</figure>
		<p>
		Our end result is a list of our choices, in order:
		<me>
			\emptyset \leq \{2\} \leq \{0\} \leq \{0,2\}
			\leq \{1\} \leq \{1,2\} \leq \{0,1\} \leq \{0,1,2\}.
		</me>
		Notice that the maximum element of <m>A</m> ended up at the <q>top</q> of the total order and the minimum element was forced to the <q>bottom</q>.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

<note><p>
	Compatible total orders are not unique: in the previous worked example, the order in which the elements of <m>A</m> were originally written represents another compatible total order:
	<me> \emptyset \leq \{0\} \leq \{1\} \leq \{2\} \leq \{0,1\} \leq \{0,2\} \leq \{1,2\} \leq \{0,1,2\} </me>.
</p></note>

</section>

